The Locust Years of Latin America
The bad news continues to accumulate these days in Latin America.
Economic conditions are deteriorating almost everywhere, social cohesion is unraveling, and political instability is growing.
It's hardly surprising, since the majority of Latin American countries have spent the last twenty years going nowhere.
The capital was sold and national debts were excessively increased, but nothing durable and beneficial was achieved.
These years have really been devoured by grasshoppers.
Over the past 20 years, the annual growth rate of GDP per capita in Latin America has averaged 0.35%.
At this rate, an economy would take 200 years to double.
In Asia, the standard of living doubles every decade.
With such anemic growth, how can Latin America hope to compete in the global marketplace except through timid wage increases?
Economic stagnation is the responsibility of a bad government, not of bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may begin to resemble Africa more and more — a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors placed her on this path.
Firstly, during the rush toward privatization, everything, from public services to manufacturing industries, was put up for auction.
For a brief moment, capital inflows helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, the revenues from privatization generated little in terms of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the liquidation of state assets was accompanied by a massive external loan.
In some cases, particularly in Argentina, the borrowing undertaken by domestic buyers has exhausted all available credit ranges.
Other countries have not fallen to the level of Argentina, but solvency is a problem in almost all Latin American countries.
Secondly, since the reform did not bring about prosperity, the region has become disillusioned.
The inflow of capital generated a wealth effect, but only as long as they existed.
When the money stopped flowing, wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would commit to another decade of structural reforms that would test the patience of average Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of in-depth reforms, too few preconditions for economic growth will be in place to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma announces the third factor: incompetent policies.
The governments that operated along technocratic lines and viewed economic growth as a rising tide that lifts all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, clumsy presidents succeed one another.
Institutions are brought down, property rights are called into question, and an effort at random and even more corrupt redistribution is underway.
Peru and Venezuela have little more chance; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacia da Silva and her team, who conduct opinion polls during the period preceding the Brazilian presidential elections, indicates that a large part of the Latin American population is ready to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the dominant economic and political ideas that capital has already started to flee—despite the elections being only a few months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but this stability may well prove to be temporary.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance deteriorates further, the economy risks a harsh landing.
As for all the good news about the emerging democracy in Mexico, its president is starting to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what to do.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate, which is endemic to the Americas.
Indeed, this is the economically speaking financial result, because where there is little savings, there is little investment—and thus little basis for accumulating capital and increasing productivity.
Venezuela now longs for the oil-rich 1970s of OPEC--years it did not participate in, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
The wealth of Argentina is now taking a vacation in Miami, perhaps permanently.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that have sold their assets and borrowed rather than saving.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates reach almost 40 percent, where the current account is in surplus, and where there is no public debt.
Government institutions support the market, and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and flexible in its learning.
Rewards for taking risks and initiative are immediate and strongly motivating.
One cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
Its per capita GDP represents only half of that of Brazil.
But with coastal regions in China growing at about 15% per year, can it seriously be doubted that within the next 15 years, it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the enormous problems encountered, things continue to proceed correctly, first and foremost due to the massive flow of foreign direct investment and the imminent benefits of joining the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to fall apart: governments backtrack on reforms and the economy loses ground against the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds flowed in, but these days are largely behind us.
Therefore, we must expect much worse economic, social, and political news in the years to come.
Demagogues such as Hugo Chávez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem—a former Argentine presidential candidate—may seem like a bad joke, but anyone who cares about the fate of Latin America should not laugh.
